ging traditional notions of women's subordination.Stranger Citizens emphasizes the making of citizenship from the perspectives of migrants themselves, and demonstrates the rich varieties and understandings of citizenship and personhood exercised by foreign migrants and refugees. O'Keefe boldly reverses the top-down model wherein citizenship was constructed only by political leaders and the courts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCitizenshipxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aCitizenshipxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aImmigrantsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aImmigrantsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Immigration.2bisacsh  awar of 1812 British Subjects, Haitian Refugees, Immigration early republic, Imigrattion 1700s, Alien and Sedition Acts.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021 Englishz978311075417908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2021z9783110753943oZDB-23-PLW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175616040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501756160423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501756160/original  a978-3-11-069046-0  Cornell Universit